column1: Will there be a new episode of mass killing in Ukraine before 1 January 2017?
column6: ['Security and Conflict']
column11: For more information on what constitutes an episode of mass killing, see the Early Warning Project's Definitions page. The Early Warning Project’s 2015 statistical risk assessments identified Ukraine as the 20th country at the greatest risk of an onset of a new episode of state-led mass killing. Those forecasts do not include the risk of mass killing by non-state groups, which would also produce a “yes” answer to this question. This question will be resolved by the Early Warning Project, in consultation with subject matter experts, using publicly available secondary sources. If the project determines that a new episode of mass killing has occurred, relevant evidence will be summarized in a post on EWP's blog. Recommended Questions Will local elections be held in the city of Donetsk before 1 January 2017? Will there be a new episode of mass killing in India before 1 January 2017? Will Dilma Rousseff cease to be President of Brazil before 1 January 2017? This question was closed as a "no" with an end date of 31 December 2016. The EWP did not find evidence of a new mass killing episode in Ukraine before the end of 2016 (Early Warning Project). See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

Ukraine is quieting down.
Political pressure

It is "all quiet on the western front". Risks are subsiding - the parties (Russia, separatists, Ukraine...) would love to solve the problem by military means, but fortunately everybody understands futility of that. IMHO the biggest risk comes from some military coup by nationalists in Kiev (events in Turkey reminded how possible is that) – too many people have guns and emotions run high (as the recent attack on the pro-Russian TV station showed). Unfortunately, this event is most probable if the current government tries to reach a settlement on the Donbas issue with Russia. As at the moment they are not inclined to go for bold moves, this risk is dropping too. Hence, I am dropping the probability of a mass killing to 0 (every day people die over there, but numbers do not add up to 1000).

Confirming previous forecast. Russia invasion of Ukraine seems likely based on the following: apparently Russian military preparedness (1), ongoing desire of Ukraine to move "west" (2,3) that are a challenge to Putin's "greater Russia" ambitions. Since U.S. hoping for Russian support in Syria significant (US) resistance to invasion may be limited, however Turkey does support Ukraine (4). While reaching the 1,000 civilian fatalities (this question) is in doubt, it seems likely Russia plans to invade and there will be a number of fatalities if/when this occurs.

If any flare up in Ukraine would occur, that may be before the US election to influence it. However, such action will not help Trump camp since his relationship with Putin is in question. So, it is unlikely that any intentional mass killing would occur.
